    {
      "name": "Rangeland Maximum Extent",
      "isActive": false,
      "meta": {
        "description": "This layer defines the observed long-term maximum extent of rangelands in Africa. It is calculated at 1km resolution using the maximum NDVI reached between 1999 and 2019 (based on SPOT/VEGETATION and PROBA-V NDVI from Copernicus). This long observation period is needed as dry areas may not receive rainfall every year and therefore may not feature detectable vegetation activity over the RAMONA 18-month target period. Considering the distribution and pattern of maximum NDVI values across Africa we defined rangeland extent as areas where the maximum long-term NDVI was between 0.15 and 0.9. These cut-offs were chosen to remove non-vegetated land (very low NDVI) and areas with highly productive (mostly closed canopy) forests (very high NDVI). N.B. For the final map we applied a 3x3 cell moving window (9 km2) to remove isolated cells by taking the mode of the window.",
        "attribution": {
          "text": "RAMONA",
          "url": "https://www.ramona.earth/"
        }
